WHEREAS, Ms. Pierce advocated for a vocational school for African-American girls to
be on the legislative agenda; in 1921, the General Assembly passed a bill creating and
recognizing the school; and
WHEREAS, the campus of Tennessee State University is home to the first collegiate
chapter of NACWC, formally known as the National Association of Colored Women's Clubs,
Incorporated, Women of Empowerment, the Frankie J. Pierce Federated Chapter; and
WHEREAS, the Frankie J. Pierce Federated Chapter of the NACWC is a select group of
like-minded young women who are dedicated to civic participation, campus involvement, and,
most importantly, community service; and
WHEREAS, the work of this esteemed chapter is a reminder of the roots Frankie Pierce
established during her nine decades of life and her lifetime of devoted advocacy and community
service; and
WHEREAS, the life and legacy of Frankie Pierce continue to have an impact on
Nashville; her tenacity and sincere desire to help others remains an inspiration to many; now,
therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the life and legacy of Juno Frankie Pierce,
founder of the Tennessee Vocational School for Colored Girls in Nashville, reflecting fondly on
her profound, enduring impact on the State of Tennessee and its citizens.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
